<Layout title="Rioja Wine Region" description="A guide to Rioja — Spain's most prestigious wine region, celebrated for its age-worthy Tempranillo and distinctive aging classifications.">
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">
    <p class="text-amber-600 font-medium tracking-wider uppercase text-sm mb-3">Wine Regions</p>
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-stone-900 mb-6">Rioja: Spain's Noble Tradition</h1>
    <p class="text-stone-500 text-sm mb-8">By Roberto Carli, CMS · 10 min read</p>

    <div class="prose prose-stone max-w-none">
      <p class="text-lg text-stone-600 leading-relaxed">Rioja is Spain's most iconic wine region and one of the best values in the world of fine wine. Where else can you buy a beautifully aged, complex red wine — released by the producer when it's actually ready to drink — for $15–$30? Rioja's aging culture is unique, generous, and increasingly appreciated by wine lovers worldwide.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Aging System</h2>
      <p>What sets Rioja apart is its <strong>classification by aging</strong> rather than vineyard hierarchy. Producers hold their wines in cellar — often for years — before release:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Joven</strong> — Young wine, released without required oak aging. Fresh, fruity, meant for immediate drinking.</li>
        <li><strong>Crianza</strong> — Minimum 2 years aging (1 year in oak). Approachable, balanced, with gentle oak influence. The everyday Rioja.</li>
        <li><strong>Reserva</strong> — Minimum 3 years aging (1 year in oak). Made only in good vintages. More complexity, structure, and depth.</li>
        <li><strong>Gran Reserva</strong> — Minimum 5 years aging (2 years in oak). Made only in exceptional vintages. Extended cellar aging produces wines of remarkable elegance, with soft tannins and evolved, tertiary aromatics.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>This system means that when you buy a Gran Reserva, the winery has already done the aging for you. A 2015 Gran Reserva released in 2021 has had 6 years of careful cellar development — no waiting required. This is a gift to consumers that most wine regions don't offer.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Three Sub-Zones</h2>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Rioja Alta</h3>
      <p>The elevated western portion, with a cooler Atlantic-influenced climate. Wines tend to be elegant, balanced, and age-worthy, with bright acidity and red fruit character. Home to many of the region's most prestigious bodegas: López de Heredia, La Rioja Alta, CVNE, and Muga.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Rioja Alavesa</h3>
      <p>The Basque Country portion, on chalky-clay soils north of the Ebro River. Produces the most aromatic, refined Rioja — often with a floral, perfumed quality. Key producers: Remelluri, Artadi, and Bodegas Ostatu.</p>

      <h3 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-6">Rioja Oriental (formerly Rioja Baja)</h3>
      <p>The lower, warmer, Mediterranean-influenced eastern zone. Wines are fuller-bodied and riper, with more alcohol and darker fruit. Garnacha (Grenache) plays a larger role here alongside Tempranillo. Traditionally used for blending, but increasingly respected for single-zone bottlings.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">The Grapes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tempranillo</strong> — The star. "Spain's noble grape" — medium to full body, cherry and plum fruit, leather, tobacco. Takes beautifully to oak aging. Called Tinto Fino in Ribera del Duero, Cencibel in La Mancha.</li>
        <li><strong>Garnacha (Grenache)</strong> — Adds warmth, fruit generosity, and body. Increasingly bottled as a single variety.</li>
        <li><strong>Graciano</strong> — Deep color, intense aromatics, high acidity. A favorite blending component for complexity.</li>
        <li><strong>Mazuelo (Carignan)</strong> — Structure and color, used in small amounts.</li>
        <li><strong>Viura (Macabeo)</strong> — The primary white grape. Ranges from fresh and crisp to rich and oak-aged. López de Heredia's Viña Tondonia Blanco (aged 6+ years before release) is one of Spain's most extraordinary white wines.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Traditional vs. Modern Rioja</h2>
      <p>Like Barolo, Rioja has experienced a stylistic debate. Traditional Rioja — epitomized by López de Heredia — uses long aging in American oak, producing wines with a distinctive vanilla, coconut, and dill character alongside developed fruit. Modern Rioja — led by producers like Artadi, Roda, and Remírez de Ganuza — favors French oak, shorter aging, more fruit concentration, and vineyard-designated bottlings.</p>
      <p>Both styles produce world-class wine. My personal preference leans traditional — there's something irreplaceable about a 20-year-old Gran Reserva with its lace-like tannins and haunting spice.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Best Values in Rioja</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Crianza</strong> from La Rioja Alta (Viña Alberdi), CVNE (Cune Crianza), or Marqués de Cáceres — $12–$18</li>
        <li><strong>Reserva</strong> from Muga, Beronia, or Bodegas Lan — $18–$28</li>
        <li><strong>Gran Reserva</strong> from CVNE (Imperial), La Rioja Alta (Viña Ardanza — technically a Reserva but aged like a Gran Reserva), or Marqués de Murrieta — $25–$45</li>
        <li><strong>White Rioja</strong> from Muga Blanco or López de Heredia Viña Gravonia — $15–$30 and utterly unique</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-stone-900 mt-10">Food Pairings</h2>
      <p>Rioja is one of the most food-friendly wines in the world. Its moderate tannins, bright acidity, and savory spice profile make it a natural partner for: roasted lamb (the classic pairing), grilled vegetables, jamón ibérico, manchego cheese, chorizo, paella, and virtually any Mediterranean cuisine. For white Rioja, try it with seafood, goat cheese, or roasted chicken.</p>
